 {"id":"mu-kex4.6.8","title":"t4c sources expansion: MCP-loaded state + project-local (justfile/Cargo/AGENTS) + per-capability provenance","description":"Cold-agent session c9ecd980 wants the manifest to merge MORE sources + tag provenance. (1) MCP: distinguish 'code-index installed' from 'code-index LOADED as MCP this session' (live mcp.* source). (2) project-local: read justfile -> project.just.*, plus Cargo/.beads/AGENTS/CLAUDE as capability/context sources. (3) per-capability 'source:' field (harness schema|PATH|curated catalog|justfile|AGENTS|memory|MCP-live) so 'live MCP says loaded' outranks 'memory says installed last week'. Extends the RegistrySource trait model (already multi-source).","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-05-29T20:14:19.482239017Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-30T02:49:35.655373653Z","closed_at":"2026-05-30T02:49:35.655294832Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["coverage","dogfood-feedback","phase-3","t4c"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"mu-kex4.6.8","depends_on_id":"mu-kex4.6","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-05-29T20:14:19.482239017Z","created_by":"tcovert","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":78,"issue_id":"mu-kex4.6.8","author":"tcovert","text":"Provenance slice DONE (green). Implemented per-capability provenance as a TREE-LEVEL fact, not a Capability field (avoids re-churning 11 constructors a 3rd time, and provenance is genuinely 'where the cap entered the tree'):\n- registry.rs: build() records path->source.name() in a parallel map; Tree::source_of(&CapPath)->Option<&str>. Because later sources win collisions, recorded provenance is always the authoritative one.\n- The bead's 'live MCP outranks memory' RANKING is already solved by add_source order (later=higher authority wins the path); provenance just makes the WINNER visible.\n- mu bridge: CapabilityView.source surfaces it on the wire (skip_serializing_if).\n- t4c 48(+1 provenance_records_the_winning_source), mu-core 407 (discover_view test asserts source). fmt+clippy clean.\n\nThe other two parts of this bead are split to their own beads (new RegistrySources, each tagged by the provenance plumbing just landed):\n- MCP-live source -> (new bead above)\n- project-local (justfile/Cargo/AGENTS/CLAUDE) -> (new bead above)\nDeferred here: CLI find/list provenance display (the mu-bridge view has it; CLI is a separate rendering surface).","created_at":"2026-05-30T02:49:35Z"}]}
 {"id":"mu-kex4.7","title":"phase1-3: update t4c-notes.md report + folkloric-capabilities data point","description":"Update scripts/t4c-notes.md: what landed, the Rust API surface, what is deferred, the human-in-loop checkpoints. Include the live-repro: this orchestrator hit folkloric-capabilities mid-session by guessing a nonexistent subcommand (agent memory get; terrain only has search/recall/recent/list/context), recovered via --help -- exactly what t4c help would have prevented. blockedBy B5,B6.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-05-29T06:53:39.560083095Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-29T17:10:42.709127473Z","closed_at":"2026-05-29T17:10:42.709036081Z","close_reason":"t4c-notes.md report write-up landed in the t4c stack; remaining phase-3 checkpoints tracked by mu-kex4.6","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["goal:2026-05-29:mu-kex4"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"mu-kex4.7","depends_on_id":"mu-kex4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-05-29T06:53:39.560083095Z","created_by":"tcovert","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"mu-kex4.7","depends_on_id":"mu-kex4.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-05-29T06:53:40.481972785Z","created_by":"tcovert","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"mu-kex4.7","depends_on_id":"mu-kex4.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-05-29T06:53:40.611290858Z","created_by":"tcovert","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"mu-kez","title":"aws-recon tool skeleton: fixture-only aws_recon tool implementing mu-039 pre-dispatch path","description":"First implementation slice of the mu-039 aws-recon skill (spec at `specs/mu-039-aws-recon-skill.md`). Tool-only; no skill-activation wiring yet. No live AWS, no runner subprocess.\n\n## Why this slice (not the whole skill)\n\nmu-039 is large: skill activation, three tool surfaces (`aws_recon`, `aws_plan_from_recon`, `aws_cloudtrail_session_events`), CloudTrail audit-join metadata, runner version capture. Doing it as one bead is a $40+ /goal and crosses too many concerns. This slice exercises the dispatch-gate landed in mu-stw end-to-end on the simplest surface (`aws_recon`) while keeping the boundary that mu-core/mu-coding never reads live AWS credentials.\n\n## Scope\n\n### In\n\n- New tool `aws_recon` registered in `crates/mu-coding/src/tools/`.\n- `ToolPolicy::required_aws_capability = Some(\"aws.scout.readonly\".into())` so the mu-stw gate refuses dispatch when the session lacks the grant.\n- Input schema (Tool::spec()): `{ capability: String, call_timeout_secs: u32, output_dir: Option<String> }` with defaults consistent with the spec (`specs/mu-039-aws-recon-skill.md:154-162`).\n- Pre-dispatch input validation:\n  1. session capability contains AwsCapability with matching name (already enforced by mu-stw; this is belt-and-suspenders / better error-shape);\n  2. `AwsCapabilityCatalog::resolve_materialized()` succeeds for `input.capability`;\n  3. catalog entry has `mutation_allowed == false`.\n  Fail-closed: any check failure → `Tool::execute` returns a structured refusal, no runner invocation, audit-shape event emitted.\n- **Dry-run/fixture execution mode**: tool reads `MU_AWS_RECON_FIXTURE_DIR` env var. If set, tool returns a stubbed `ReconReport` (artifact path = fixture path); if unset, tool returns `not-yet-implemented` refusal with a structured error. This proves the dispatch path + catalog resolution without standing up the runner.\n- Test cases:\n  - dispatch refused when session lacks `aws.scout.readonly` (already tested via mu-stw; mirror here at tool granularity);\n  - catalog miss → structured error;\n  - `mutation_allowed: true` entry → structured error;\n  - fixture-mode happy path → ReconReport returned with expected shape;\n  - fixture-unset → not-yet-implemented refusal (this branch will be replaced when runner wiring lands).\n- Audit metadata captured on every dispatch (success or refusal): mu session id, capability name, catalog digest, local AWS profile name from catalog, role ARN from catalog. No STS metadata yet (fixture mode has none).\n\n### Out\n\n- Skill activation surface (the `SkillActivation`/`ToolSchema` spans that the full mu-039 spec produces). Tool stands alone; operator manually grants `aws.scout.readonly` for tests.\n- The other two mu-039 tools (`aws_plan_from_recon`, `aws_cloudtrail_session_events`) — each gets its own bead.\n- Actually invoking `scripts/mu-aws-capability-run.sh` + `scripts/aws-recon.sh`. Runner wiring is a follow-on bead so the boundary is clean.\n- STS / CloudTrail audit-join. Audit-shape struct lands here but the optional fields stay None in fixture mode.\n- biscuit-auth, cross-daemon attenuation.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- New tool registered; mu-coding exposes it.\n- All test cases above pass.\n- `cargo test --workspace` green.\n- `cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` green.\n- `cargo fmt --check` green.\n- Commit cites `specs/mu-039-aws-recon-skill.md:<lines>` for the spec references it implements.\n\n## Design notes (decide at impl time)\n\n- Where does the catalog live? mu-core owns the types (mu-ysh). Tool needs an instance. Options: (a) operator pre-loads via env var path; (b) tool takes a catalog handle injected at registration time. Lean (b) so tests can inject in-memory catalogs; env-var path resolution is the operator-facing default that produces a catalog handle at startup.\n- ReconReport shape: minimal v1 = `{ artifact_dir: PathBuf, catalog_digest: String, capability: String }`. Real fields land when runner wiring lands.\n- Error type: re-use the structured error shape from mu-stw's dispatch refusal so the audit fields are uniform across pre-dispatch refusal and Tool::execute refusal.\n\n## Why this matters\n\nmu-stw landed the dispatch gate but nothing exercises it yet. This bead is the smallest concrete tool that proves: capability gate fires correctly, catalog resolution path works, fixture-mode lets us iterate on tool ergonomics + audit shape without touching live AWS. After this lands, mu-fb0 (live-loop adoption) + the runner-wiring bead can compose independently.\n\n## References\n\n- Spec: `specs/mu-039-aws-recon-skill.md`\n- Dispatch gate: `crates/mu-core/src/agent/loop_.rs` (mu-stw, PR #8)\n- Capability catalog: `crates/mu-core/src/aws.rs` (mu-ysh, PR #2)\n- Tool surface convention: existing tools in `crates/mu-coding/src/tools/`","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"tcovert","created_at":"2026-05-14T15:20:12.686457593Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-14T17:05:27.434158016Z","closed_at":"2026-05-14T17:05:27.434087324Z","close_reason":"Merged in PR #10 as 3aec957","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aws","capability","fixtures","mu-coding","recon","tools"]}
+{"id":"mu-kgpg","title":"Session command append can reorder against normal session events","description":"Post-merge review of PR #275 found a sequencing hole in `SessionEventLog`: `append_command` serializes command-vs-command writes by holding `disk_writer` across id assignment/write/fsync, but normal `append()` assigns event ids outside that lock and writes through `write_to_disk()` separately. A normal append can reserve id N, then a concurrent command append can reserve/write/push id N+1, then the normal append writes/pushes id N, leaving disk/snapshot physical order out of id order.\n\nWhy it matters: PR #275 relies on event-log order as a projection substrate for command/receipt pipelines. Comments only claim disk order matches id order for concurrent command appends, but consumers may reasonably assume JSONL/event vector order is chronological/id order for the whole session log. This can make receipt/command/event projections surprising under concurrent gateway events and agent/forwarder appends.\n\nRequired fix: introduce one append/sequencing critical section for all session event appends, with strict vs best-effort durability as a mode, or otherwise make both `append` and `append_command` share id assignment -> disk write -> memory push ordering. Add a concurrency test that interleaves normal append with command append and asserts on-disk and snapshot ids are monotonic.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-06-11T18:48:03.202032604Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-06-11T18:48:03.202032604Z","source_repo":"mu","source_repo_path":"<local-path>","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["correctness","event-log","mu-046","pr275"]}
 {"id":"mu-kgu","title":"CompactionPolicy trait — pluggable context-compaction strategies, benchmarkable","description":"Add a `CompactionPolicy` trait as a sibling to `CacheStrategy` and `ProviderRenderer`. Per-session config picks the policy. The rope substrate (post-mu-fb0) is the substrate it operates over.\n\n## Why\n\nClaude Code's compaction on 1M-context Opus 4.7 takes ~5 minutes — a full-context model pass to re-summarize the conversation. mu can do better because:\n\n1. The typed event log lets compaction reason about WHAT to compact at the structural level (span families: file-loads where files have changed, tool-call clusters whose results already landed in the rope, expired skill activations) BEFORE any model call.\n2. Compaction creates a natural new stable prefix → composes with `CacheStrategy` so the next ask pays one cache-creation cost then enjoys cache hits. Claude Code's \"rewrite transcript\" path always invalidates cache.\n3. As a separate POLICY (not baked into the loop), strategies can be swapped/tested/benchmarked independently. Same architectural pattern as mu-ktq's `CacheStrategy`.\n\nOperator (tcovert) note: \"I don't claim to be an expert on compaction correctness; now that we have the primitives we can take research literature or our own testing and try to optimize.\"\n\n## Scope\n\n### In\n\n- New `CompactionPolicy` trait in `crates/mu-core/src/context/compaction.rs`.\n- Trait shape (proposed): `fn compact(&self, rope: &RetainedRope, target_tokens: usize) -> CompactionResult`. `CompactionResult` carries: new rope, decision log (which spans dropped/merged/summarized), token-savings estimate, optional model-call required (e.g. for natural-language summarization).\n- Provider trait method (analogous to `cache_strategy()`): `fn provider.compaction_policy() -> Arc<dyn CompactionPolicy>` so providers can declare their preferred default.\n- At least one concrete policy: `NoCompactionPolicy` (no-op, the v1 default — preserves current behavior).\n- At least one heuristic policy (probably `SpanFamilyDropPolicy`): drops/summarizes by span-kind priority (skill-activations > recent tool-results > stale file-loads > old assistant turns), zero model calls.\n- Benchmark harness: take a corpus of stored ropes (could seed from mu-upb's per-session JSONLs), apply each policy, record (input_tokens, output_tokens, time_ms, optional model_calls, retention_metrics).\n- Integration with the agent loop: trigger compaction when input_tokens crosses a per-session threshold (configurable; sensible default = 70% of model's context window).\n\n### Out\n\n- The intelligent-summarization model-call policy. Whether to invoke a cheap model to compress narrative spans is its own bead — `mu-compaction-llm-summary` once research informs design.\n- Streaming compaction (compact during streaming rather than between turns).\n- Persisting compacted ropes to disk (separate concern from compute path).\n- Quality-grader infrastructure — that's its own bead but mu-pex (metrics framework) is the right home; this bead notes the dependency.\n\n## Design questions to resolve (at impl time)\n\n1. **Compaction trigger**: per-turn check, or only when token threshold crossed? Lean: threshold-crossed, since per-turn checks add latency.\n2. **In-place vs. produce-new-rope**: should `compact()` mutate the rope or return a new one? Lean: new (immutable substrate per the architecture's design).\n3. **Decision-log shape**: which spans were dropped + reasons. Operator-view consumes this for \"what did we lose?\" visibility. Lean: structured `Vec<CompactionDecision>` where each decision is `{ span_id, action: Drop/Merge/Summarize, reason }`.\n4. **Heuristic priority ordering**: which span-kinds get dropped first? Spec-aware ordering (file-loads with mtime mismatch > old tool-results > old assistant-text > skill-activations > tool-schemas > system) seems right but should be empirical.\n\n## Correctness model\n\nUnlike `CacheStrategy` (which has byte-for-byte correctness — boundary on last stable cacheable span), compaction correctness is FUZZY:\n\n- Outcome-based: did the model produce a correct answer after compaction?\n- Proxy-based: did the post-compaction prompt later reference span IDs that were dropped? (audit-shape regression test).\n- Quality-proxy: structural-grader from protocol-eval framework, comparing full-context-response vs. compacted-context-response on a shared corpus.\n\nBenchmark infrastructure has to support outcome/proxy/quality measurements, not just timing+token-count.\n\n## Composition\n\n- **mu-fb0 (closed)**: rope is now the live working state. CompactionPolicy operates on rope. Required prerequisite — satisfied.\n- **mu-pex (open)**: metrics framework is the natural home for compaction quality dashboards. Compaction emits per-call metrics into mu-pex's pipeline.\n- **mu-ktq (closed)**: trait pattern (CacheStrategy, ProviderRenderer) — CompactionPolicy follows the same shape.\n- **mu-upb (closed)**: per-session JSONL logs on disk become the natural corpus for benchmark replay (load a real session's events, project to rope, compact, compare).\n\n## Research/literature dependencies\n\nCompaction is a live research area. Worth surveying before committing to design:\n- Anthropic's documented context-engineering best practices (claude.com/docs/context-engineering)\n- LangChain/LlamaIndex's `ConversationSummaryMemory` patterns\n- Recent papers on long-context model retention (memory module ideas)\n- Claude Code's own compaction trigger/strategy (visible via the public CLI behavior — 5-min compaction on 1M context is the observable artifact)\n\nOperator's framing: \"now that we have the primitives, we can take research literature or our own testing and try to optimize.\" This bead unblocks that research-driven optimization phase.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `CompactionPolicy` trait + `NoCompactionPolicy` + at least one heuristic policy land in `crates/mu-core/src/context/compaction.rs`.\n- Per-session config selects the policy; defaults to `NoCompactionPolicy` (preserves v1 behavior).\n- Agent loop invokes `policy.compact()` when token threshold crossed.\n- Compaction emits a structured event (similar to ContextAssembly) so the operator can audit decisions.\n- Benchmark harness with at least 3 corpus ropes; outputs (input_tokens, output_tokens, time_ms, decision_log).\n- Tests: heuristic policy preserves \"load-bearing\" spans (tool-schemas, recent assistant turns); drops correctly identified stale spans; cache-boundary composition works (compacted prefix becomes a new cacheable boundary).\n- `cargo test --workspace` green, `cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` green, `cargo fmt --check` green.\n\n## Notes\n\nFiled 2026-05-14 after mu-fb0 merged the rope-as-live-state infrastructure. Conversation context: operator noted Claude Code's ~5-minute compaction on 1M Opus 4.7; suspected mu's would be faster. The trait-based separation is what enables benchmarking, A/B testing, and research-driven evolution — without coupling each new policy to the agent loop's internals.","notes":"## Anthropic's published mechanism (verified 2026-05-14)\n\nPer Anthropic's API docs (`platform.claude.com/docs/en/build-with-claude/compaction`):\n- Mechanism: **full model inference call** (\"the same model specified in your request performs the summarization\").\n- Default trigger: 150k input tokens.\n- Output shape: free-form natural-language summary wrapped in a `compaction` content block.\n- Replacement: on subsequent requests, messages before the compaction block are auto-dropped; conversation continues from the summary.\n\nNOT a mark-spans / structured-marks approach. NOT a heuristic. NOT documented: the internal prompt or any preservation rules.\n\n## Design ladder (operator-designed, three rungs of judge+executor sophistication)\n\nThe ladder splits the model's job (judgment) from mu's job (rope surgery). Each rung trades output-size for cross-pass identity.\n\n### Rung A: full-hash output (mu-kgu.3, landed in PR #22)\n\n```text\nINPUT to judge:\n  <hash> [span_kind] preview...\n  <hash> [span_kind] preview...\n\nOUTPUT from judge:\n  { \"keep\": [\"<hash>\", \"<hash>\", ...], \"summary\": \"<paragraph>\" }\n```\n\n- Output: ~700-2000 tokens (keep-list hashes ~300 tokens + summary ~500 tokens)\n- ~5-10x cheaper than Anthropic's free-form-summary approach\n- Hashes are content-stable across compaction passes (useful for audit/replay)\n\n### Rung B: index-based keep-list (mu-kgu.7, follow-on optimization)\n\nOperator design (2026-05-14): \"you're sending an index for the active context → hash → string, so all that needs to come back is the short id of the index items to keep. That's even smaller than the last idea.\"\n\n```text\nINPUT to judge:\n  #1 [span_kind] preview...  hash=abc12345\n  #2 [span_kind] preview...  hash=def67890\n\nOUTPUT from judge:\n  { \"keep\": [1, 4, 7, 12], \"summary\": \"<paragraph>\" }\n```\n\n- Output: ~200-700 tokens (keep-list integers ~50 tokens + summary ~500 tokens)\n- ~6x cheaper than Rung A's keep-list portion\n- Indices are pass-local; mu maps `#N → span` and preserves hashes server-side for provenance\n- The judge model doesn't need cross-pass identity (it's one-shot judgment); hashes only matter to the operator and the rope's audit log\n\n### Rung C: future research — when \"judge\" itself wants memory\n\nIf a future iteration wants the judge to maintain cross-call state (e.g. \"this span has been kept across three compactions; lower the bar to drop it\"), hash-based output regains the audit-stability advantage. Defer until evidence motivates it.\n\n## Recommendation\n\nShip rung A in mu-kgu.3 (current PR #22). File mu-kgu.7 as the rung B optimization once mu-kgu.3 has landed and benchmark numbers exist to compare against. The benchmark harness from mu-kgu.5 is the right home for measuring the rung A → rung B delta.\n\n## New policy: HashAndSummaryPolicy (rung A, judge + executor, single call)\n\nHow it works (single model call) — preserved here for archeology, full algorithm in mu-kgu.3's bead body:\n\n1. Build span-index: each span gets stable 8-char hex hash + span_kind tag + ~80-160 char preview + full content.\n2. Judge prompt: given the span sequence, return `{keep, summary}`.\n3. Surgery: kept hashes preserve verbatim with provenance; others absorbed into one new CompactionSummary span.\n4. Result: kept spans (verbatim) + one summary span at the position of the earliest absorbed span.\n\n## Why this is a strategic differentiator\n\nIf rung A benchmarks confirm wall-clock under ~10 seconds (vs claude-code's 5 minutes), that's a categorical UX difference. Rung B compounds the win further. Combined with the verbatim-retention property (auditable, replayable), the \"mu has better compaction than claude-code\" message lands clearly.\n\n## Ladder of compaction policies (existing positions)\n\n1. NoCompactionPolicy — do nothing (mu-kgu.1, landed).\n2. SpanFamilyDropPolicy — heuristic span-kind drops, zero model calls (mu-kgu.2, landed).\n3. **HashAndSummaryPolicy rung A** — full-hash output (mu-kgu.3, in PR #22).\n4. **HashAndSummaryPolicy rung B** — index-based keep-list (mu-kgu.7, follow-on).\n5. AnthropicLikePolicy — full-model summarize-and-replace (matches claude-code today).\n6. Future rung C — judge-with-memory.\n\nEach rung is a separate policy implementing the CompactionPolicy trait. Benchmarks compare them via the mu-kgu.5 harness.","status":"open","priority":3,"issue_type":"feature","owner":"tcovert","created_at":"2026-05-14T17:49:43.015850833Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-14T19:03:02.018812720Z","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["agent-loop","architecture","compaction","mu-pex","policy","research"]}
 {"id":"mu-kgu.1","title":"mu-compaction-foundation: CompactionPolicy trait + NoCompactionPolicy + stubs","description":"Phase 1 of the mu-kgu prototype. Lays the trait surface that Phase 2's three parallel workers fill in.\n\n## Scope\n\n### In\n\n- New module `crates/mu-core/src/context/compaction.rs` with:\n  - `pub trait CompactionPolicy: Send + Sync` — method: `fn compact(&self, rope: &RetainedRope, target_tokens: usize) -> CompactionResult;`\n  - `pub struct CompactionResult { rope: RetainedRope, decisions: Vec<CompactionDecision>, tokens_before: usize, tokens_after: usize, wall_clock_ms: u64 }`\n  - `pub enum CompactionDecision { Kept { span_id: String }, Dropped { span_id: String, reason: String }, Summarized { absorbed_span_ids: Vec<String>, summary_span_id: String } }`\n  - `pub struct NoCompactionPolicy;` — `compact()` returns the rope unchanged + an empty decisions Vec\n- Stub modules at `crates/mu-core/src/context/compaction/{heuristic,hash_summary}.rs`:\n  - `pub struct SpanFamilyDropPolicy;` and `pub struct HashAndSummaryPolicy { judge_provider: Arc<dyn Provider> }` (or similar)\n  - Both impl `CompactionPolicy` with `todo!(\\\"see mu-compaction-heuristic / mu-compaction-hash-summary\\\")` in `compact()`\n- `Provider` trait addition (in `crates/mu-core/src/agent/provider.rs`):\n  - `fn compaction_policy(&self) -> Arc<dyn CompactionPolicy> { Arc::new(crate::context::compaction::NoCompactionPolicy) }` with default impl preserving v1 behavior\n- Wire into `crates/mu-core/src/context/mod.rs` and `crates/mu-core/src/lib.rs`\n- Unit tests:\n  - `CompactionResult` serde round-trips\n  - `NoCompactionPolicy::compact()` is idempotent (input rope == output rope)\n  - `Provider::compaction_policy()` default returns NoCompactionPolicy (verify via TypeId or Arc::ptr_eq pattern)\n\n### Out\n\n- Any real compaction logic (Phase 2)\n- Agent-loop integration (separate bead, mu-compaction-loop-integration)\n- Benchmark harness (separate, mu-compaction-benchmark-harness)\n\n## Why this is the gatekeeper\n\nPhase 2's three workers each need an agreed-upon trait surface to fill in. If the trait shape isn't locked here, the three workers will diverge and merge becomes painful. Invest in clean Phase 1 → save 2+ hours of conflict-resolution later.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- All listed types + trait + stubs compile.\n- `cargo test --workspace` green (no regression on existing tests).\n- `cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` green.\n- `cargo fmt --check` green.\n- Commit message cites mu-kgu + this bead.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","owner":"tcovert","created_at":"2026-05-14T18:01:13.756826102Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-14T19:07:28.704545858Z","closed_at":"2026-05-14T19:07:28.704474006Z","close_reason":"Merged in PR #19","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["agent-loop","architecture","compaction"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"mu-kgu.1","depends_on_id":"mu-kgu","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-05-14T18:01:13.756826102Z","created_by":"tcovert","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"mu-kgu.10","title":"mu-kgu.10: replace chars/4 token estimator with real tokenizer (tiktoken-rs) for headline-comparable numbers","description":"Replace mu's `estimate_tokens(spans) -> usize` (currently `chars().count()` per span) with a real-tokenizer implementation. Without this, mu's reported \"tokens_before / tokens_after\" numbers in benchmarks and `ContextAssembly` events use a different ruler than Anthropic's measured token counts — which prevents direct headline comparisons in the README.\n\n## The miscount\n\nIn the mu-kgu.9 calibration (2026-05-14), mu's estimator reported the test corpus at ~81k tokens; Anthropic's real tokenizer (via `usage.iterations[].input_tokens` on the same corpus) measured 124,091 tokens. **~50% under-count**. Ratios (`tokens_after / tokens_before`) are preserved internally, but absolute magnitudes can't be cross-referenced with external sources.\n\n## Why P1\n\nThis is the load-bearing piece for any README-level claim about token reduction or cost savings. We need mu's \"the heuristic reduces 240k tokens to 18k in 19µs\" to use the SAME 240k number Anthropic would report on the same input. Otherwise the math doesn't compose cleanly and skeptical readers can't verify our claims independently.\n\n## Scope\n\n### In\n\n- Add dependency: `tiktoken-rs = \"0.x\"` (well-maintained MIT-licensed Rust port of OpenAI's tiktoken).\n- Replace `estimate_tokens(spans)` body to use tiktoken-rs (the `cl100k_base` encoding is the closest public approximation of Anthropic's tokenizer — both are BPE schemes with similar compression ratios).\n- Document the substitution: tiktoken-rs is not Anthropic's actual tokenizer (Anthropic's is undocumented), but the count is close enough for budget-shape decisions and headline-comparable numbers. Acceptable error: ±5%.\n- Update `span_size()` in `heuristic.rs` to delegate to the shared estimator (it already does, post mu-metrics-cleanup).\n- Re-run the benchmark; update the cleanup-writeup numbers in `~/.claude-personal/experiments/path-a-compaction-calibration-2026-05-14.md` if material.\n\n### Out\n\n- Per-provider tokenizers (OpenAI vs Anthropic vs Gemini all use slightly different schemes). v1 uses one tokenizer for all; per-provider can be a follow-up if needed.\n- A *true* Anthropic tokenizer port. Anthropic doesn't publish theirs; we approximate via tiktoken.\n- Server-side count_tokens API call. Too slow for in-bench-loop use. Useful for one-off calibration; not for the estimator.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- `estimate_tokens(spans)` uses tiktoken (cl100k_base).\n- mu's reported tokens are within ±5% of Anthropic's `usage.iterations[].input_tokens` on the same input.\n- Existing tests still pass (test fixtures use ASCII content where char/4 ≈ tiktoken count; minor assertion updates may be needed).\n- Benchmark output is now headline-comparable: \"mu reduced 124k tokens to 6k in 19µs\" can be cited next to \"Anthropic compacted 124k tokens to 2.3k in 38s\" with consistent units.\n- cargo test --workspace green; clippy -D warnings; fmt --check.\n\n## Cost calibration: re-run\n\nAfter landing, re-run the Path A calibration script + mu's bench to produce a clean joint table with consistent token units. Update README candidates.\n\n## References\n\n- mu-kgu.9 calibration writeup: `~/.claude-personal/experiments/path-a-compaction-calibration-2026-05-14.md` (notes the ~50% divergence)\n- Current estimator: `crates/mu-core/src/context/compaction.rs::estimate_tokens`\n- tiktoken-rs: https://github.com/zurawiki/tiktoken-rs\n\n## Provenance\n\nOperator (2026-05-14): \"it might be worth looking at the tokens part now. This seems like a headline for our readme that we'd want any potential visitors to see.\"\n\nFiled 2026-05-14, immediately after mu-kgu.9's measurement surfaced the divergence as the load-bearing accuracy gap for any external claim.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","owner":"tcovert","created_at":"2026-05-14T20:39:58.828271971Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-14T21:16:38.834316193Z","closed_at":"2026-05-14T21:16:38.834246252Z","close_reason":"Merged in PR #34 as 78cf81a","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["benchmark","calibration","estimator","headline","tokenizer"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"mu-kgu.10","depends_on_id":"mu-kgu","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-05-14T20:39:58.828271971Z","created_by":"tcovert","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
