 {"id":"mu-loop-retry-text-accumulator-leak-s545","title":"codex provider: message output-item boundaries discarded — multi-item responses fuse into one jammed text block","description":"SYMPTOM (operator capture from the jg9p.1 mu-solo session, 2026-06-05): assistant message rendered with its opening duplicated mid-message, jammed without whitespace ('...if you want, or hold.No worries. I'll hold on the AI review...'). Preceded by two turns showing 'x provider: codex returned 503 Service Unavailable ... (turn ended, no output)'.\n\nEVIDENCE — THE DURABLE EVENT IS CORRUPTED (renderer exonerated): daemon 2f270bcba43f305d session-1, assistant_message_event id 2515 contains 'No worries' TWICE within the single event. Unlike mu-solo-scrollback-dup-recommit-8hva (renderer-only, events clean), here the SOURCE OF TRUTH carries the duplication.\n\nSTRUCTURE OF THE CORRUPT MESSAGE: [Response A: 'No worries. I noticed the PR bookmark didn't move ... finalize the jj change/push if you want, or hold.'] immediately followed by [Response B: 'No worries. I'll hold on the AI review until you point me at the right script/env. Current state: #184 exists...'] — two independently-generated responses to the same prompt, mechanically concatenated (no whitespace at the seam).\n\nMECHANISM HYPOTHESIS: attempt A streamed partial deltas then died (503 mid-stream); a retry (loop-level — the codex provider itself retries only on 401, openai_codex.rs:12,1174) regenerated from scratch; the text/delta assembly buffer was NOT cleared between attempts, so the final committed message = A-partial + B-full. Trace where the loop (crates/mu-core/src/agent/loop_/) or forwarder accumulates streamed text and what happens to that buffer when a stream errors and the call is retried.\n\nSEVERITY NOTE: P1 because the event log is mu's source of truth — downstream consumers (rehydration, replay, analytics, compaction judges, the web console) all inherit the corruption.\n\nRELATED: mu-wf5w (turn lost — same turn-lifecycle machinery, loss direction; the two '(turn ended, no output)' error turns in this capture may BE wf5w manifestations), mu-solo-scrollback-dup-recommit-8hva (renderer-side duplication, fixed separately — diagnosis discipline identical: event log decides which layer).","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","assignee":"cc-personal-ec4a0b48","created_at":"2026-06-05T17:07:43.647258579Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-06-05T19:10:37.085376942Z","closed_at":"2026-06-05T19:10:37.085281689Z","close_reason":"done","closed_by_session":"ec4a0b48-9dd9-4d05-8867-03bcfa5b8b0e","source_repo":"mu","source_repo_path":"<mu-checkout>","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["agent-loop","event-log","mu-core","providers"],"comments":[{"id":146,"issue_id":"mu-loop-retry-text-accumulator-leak-s545","author":"tcovert","text":"RE-DIAGNOSIS (2026-06-05, terrain-checked): the retained-buffer-across-retry mechanism is REFUTED. (1) Both 503s were 'reset before headers' — the SSE stream never opened on the failed attempts; zero tokens existed to retain. (2) events_stream state (accumulated_text) is constructed fresh per stream() call (openai_codex.rs ~770); no cross-call state. (3) The agent loop has NO retry — handle_invoke_llm returns Err(Outcome::Error) and the ask ends (done id 2502/2509 stop=error). (4) The two fused takes answer DIFFERENT messages: take 1 responds to u2497 'l' / u2504 'sorry wrong window', take 2 to u2511 'finding the script you need' — three UMs accumulated unanswered in history because the two errored asks had already pushed theirs. REVISED MECHANISM: the third (successful) response very likely contained TWO message output items (model answering the backlog as two messages — natural for the Responses API); the adapter flattens ALL output_text.delta frames into one undelimited accumulator — OutputItemAdded/Done only handle FunctionCall; message-item boundaries are ignored (assemble_content emits one jammed Text block; the whitespace-free seam '...or hold.No worries.' is the flatten signature). FIX SHAPE: track message-item boundaries per output_index and emit them delimited (separate Text blocks, or join with \\n\\n); unit-testable against an SSE fixture with two message items in openai_codex tests — no live repro needed. Title's 'retry/leak' framing is stale; scope is now: codex adapter loses output-item boundaries.","created_at":"2026-06-05T18:53:31Z"}]}
 {"id":"mu-lpt","title":"mu-tui: status-bar glyph legend (sys: indicator and similar)","description":"## Problem\n\nThe `sys:` glyph in the top-right of the status bar (✓ when default system\nprompt set, · when not — line 1953 of mu-tui/src/main.rs, from mu-62s)\nisn't discoverable. User report: \"sys: — not sure what it's for.\"\n\n## Proposal\n\nSurface the meaning. Lightest-touch options:\n\n(a) Press-and-hold key (e.g., `?` over the status bar) to show a legend\n    popup explaining each glyph\n(b) F1 → \"status bar legend\" section listing each indicator\n(c) Brief hint in `:help` output\n\nA direct contextual expansion would be too noisy in the status bar itself\n(e.g., `sys:✓ (default system prompt set; :system_prompt to view)`), but\nthe legend popup or help entry achieves the same with on-demand access.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n- User can determine what `sys:` (and similar glyphs) mean without\n  reading source code\n- Discovery path doesn't require knowing the right command in advance\n\n## Cross-refs\n\n- mu-62s (added the indicator)\n- Provenance: TUI feedback (mu daemon f3845422 session-2, 2026-05-15)","status":"open","priority":4,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-05-16T01:38:31.032885992Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-16T01:38:31.032885992Z","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["documentation","dx","mu-tui","status-bar"]}
 {"id":"mu-lsp-tool-source-o2wc","title":"mu-047: LSP servers as a tool source — hover/definition/references/diagnostics as agent tools","description":"Scoped 2026-06-10 with tcovert (spec mu-047 to be written before code). Shape: exactly parallel to MCP import — an lsp_client module manages LSP server lifecycle per workspace root and exposes lsp_hover / lsp_definition / lsp_references / lsp_diagnostics / lsp_symbols as agent-loop tools (gateway work, INV-10-clean; read-only so they classify PermissionLevel::Allow like code_recall). Complements code-index, not replaces: recall answers 'where is the concept', LSP answers 'what exactly is this symbol and who calls it'; diagnostics give the model compiler feedback without a full cargo check round trip. tcovert's stated goal: 'develop the ability to offer LSP connections to the models.'","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-06-11T22:15:28.313313897Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-06-11T22:15:28.313313897Z","source_repo":"mu","source_repo_path":"<mu-checkout>","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"mu-lr2y","title":"Centralize request method metadata for routing, journaling, redaction, and query policy","description":"Post-merge review of PR #275 and operator review comments identified repeated method truth tables across the ingest pipeline: `classify(method)`, `QUERY_METHODS`/`is_query`, `addressed_session_id`, `SECRET_PARAM_FIELDS`, receipt error/stage classification, and MCP mirror comments/tests. No concrete wrong table entry was found in the review, but the shape is brittle: adding a request method requires updating several parallel matches/arrays or the method can be routed, journaled, redacted, or elided incorrectly.
+
+Recommended fix: define a single request-method metadata surface (trait or table) such as `MethodMeta { method, scope, query, session_id_param, secret_fields, mcp_aliases/handler_kind }`, with request types or their metadata owning these facts. Outer code should delegate to the metadata instead of re-matching method strings in multiple places. Add tests that iterate the metadata registry and assert dispatch/ingest/query/redaction behavior derives from it.
+
+This is a maintainability/refactor item, not a known production bug, but it protects mu-046 command journal invariants as the protocol surface grows.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-06-11T18:48:13.767995417Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-06-11T18:48:13.767995417Z","source_repo":"mu","source_repo_path":"<local-path>","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["maintainability","mu-046","pr275","refactor"]}
 {"id":"mu-luof","title":"GOAL 2026-05-19: delegate-then-review experiment — multi-line prompt as target for protocol iteration","description":"## Tracking bead for /goal session 2026-05-19 (overnight)\n\nMethodology experiment. The PRIMARY DELIVERABLE is **a working delegation-then-review-then-postmortem loop**, with multi-line-prompt-growing-upward as the example task.\n\nThe CODE deliverable is secondary. If the delegation infrastructure produces a usable PR but the methodology doesn't iterate cleanly, the experiment is a partial success. If the methodology lessons are sharp but the PR has bugs, the experiment is still useful.\n\n## Crew\n\n| Role | Backend | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Orchestrator | claude-code (this session) | Sets up, monitors, PR review, postmortem |\n| Worker | claude-code via `agent-router --auth claude-oauth` | Implements |\n| Reviewer | gpt-5.5-codex via `agent-router --auth codex-oauth --tools read,grep` | Reviews worker's output pre-PR |\n\n(Pot isolation deferred — mu-fpgd / claude-in-pot is still blocked. Working without it tonight.)\n\n## Sub-beads (tagged `goal:2026-05-19:<this-bead-id>`)\n\n1. **Implementation**: multi-line prompt growing upward in F3 inline mode (filed below)\n2. **Reviewer dispatch**: gpt-5.5 reads worker's commit + spec, returns approve/iterate verdict (filed below)\n3. **Postmortem**: orchestrator reviews PR, writes postmortem on protocol + output, captures protocol-refinement suggestions (filed below)\n\nEach sub-bead has stop criteria + acceptance + budget cap.\n\n## Hypothesis (pre-registered)\n\n- Worker can implement the multi-line prompt within ~$20 budget (~200 LOC at conservative 10:1)\n- Reviewer can return a usable verdict within ~$2 budget\n- Postmortem will surface 1-3 protocol refinement candidates\n- End-to-end wall-clock: ~2-3 hours including the model latency for both worker + reviewer\n\n## Stop criteria (in addition to default seven)\n\n- Worker exceeds budget cap → halt + postmortem fires on partial work\n- Reviewer's verdict is 'iterate' but worker hits 2 iteration cycles without convergence → halt + postmortem on the methodology, not the code\n- Anything touches files outside crates/mu-tui/src/ → halt (scope creep tripwire)\n\n## Anti-success modes the experiment can detect\n\n- Worker silently produces a HollowCommit (claim mismatches diff) — forensics classifier would catch this; orchestrator verifies via verify-claims gate\n- Worker silently produces a NarrativeNoAction (commit but no functional change) — verify-claims + cargo test catches\n- Reviewer rubber-stamps without reading — protocol check: reviewer's output must cite file:line; orchestrator audits this\n\n## Post-experiment artifact\n\n`MORNING_2026-05-19.md` at repo root with:\n- What landed (PR # + commit list)\n- Process timeline (worker dispatch → review → iterations → PR)\n- Surprises observed\n- Suggested protocol refinements (concrete bullet points; if any, also file as beads against the goal-protocol SKILL.md)\n- Cost / turns / wall-clock actuals vs predictions\n\n## Provenance\n\nOperator (2026-05-19, pre-sleep): 'take a task, like the expanding prompt box, and delegate to the work crew, set the goals, stop criteria, success, etc. After gpt reviews the code and says it's ready for PR. You review the PR. Then, you can do a postmortem on the process and output, and think about what you might change to the protocol. And repeat. Science with the system.'","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-05-19T06:36:16.762842573Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-19T06:36:16.762842573Z","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["delegation","experiment","goal-tracking","mu-o1y7","protocol-iteration"]}
 {"id":"mu-lvb6","title":"t4c policy gate door A: advise-only bash-dispatch gate + event-logged decisions (spec + skeleton)","description":"From the gh-merge-caveat design discussion (operator's five-options riff, mu session 7517502faa5f7ed2 event 2502-2506, + director layering analysis 2026-06-07). THE IDEA: t4c grows from a discovery surface into a policy surface — the bash tool consults the t4c library at its dispatch chokepoint (the single verified point established by mu-n25a/mu-cvm5) before exec. Capability entries gain a non-display policy block (rule = matcher + predicate set + action + message) in the same catalog config — advice and guardrail are one record, structurally cannot drift.\n\nARCHITECTURE LAYERING (record this in the spec): this is the missing ARGUMENT-LEVEL layer between tonight's CLASS-level gate and future OS sandboxing:\n  capability ceiling (class: may this TOOL run?)  <- mu-n25a/cvm5, shipped\n  t4c policy (content: may this INVOCATION run?)  <- this bead\n  capsicum (OS: what can the process touch?)      <- mu-627\nIt is the FOURTH consumer of the side_effects taxonomy (after dispatch gate, fork attenuation, capsicum — mu-8stm throughline): policy rules should speak the SAME vocabulary (a rewrite reduces effective blast radius; do not grow a second severity language).\n\nDOOR A SCOPE (this bead): advise-only — gate warns, command runs anyway. Fail-open by design while rules earn trust. REQUIRED PROPERTIES: (1) every gate decision (advise/reject/rewrite, rule id, original command, predicate results) is an EVENT in the session log — the forensics/stats layer sees it; false-positive RATE, not intuition, is the graduation evidence; (2) gate messages carry rule id + how to inspect the rule + the override path (MU_GATE_OVERRIDE-style, logged) — the gate's own output is model-facing terrain and a wrong rule must be inspectable/countermandable, not a confident misdirection loop; (3) predicate vocabulary is a CLOSED Rust enum (cwd-is-jj-colocated, repo match, subcommand match, flag present) — pressure for richer predicates ('PR has >N commits') is a signal the rule belongs in code, not config: do not build a half-language; (4) rewrite action exists in the schema but is LOUD-ONLY ('t4c: rewrote X->Y; reason; original: ...') and opt-in per rule — silent rewrite is an invisible-decision surface and is banned (operator principle: a framework that makes decisions you can't inspect or override is working against you).\n\nRule #1: gh pr merge --delete-branch under cwd-is-jj-colocated -> advise (later reject via door B, mu-XXXX). Deliverable: short spec.md + schema + bash-tool consult + the events + rule #1.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-06-07T18:04:09.116365180Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-06-07T18:04:34.163489387Z","source_repo":"mu","source_repo_path":"<mu-checkout>","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"mu-lwiu","title":"Split mu-tui/src/main.rs (4530 LOC) into app/* + render/* modules","description":"## Problem\n\ncrates/mu-tui/src/main.rs is 4530 lines. The single App struct has ~35 fields. The App impl handles input, command-palette dispatch, RPC calls, render coordination, AND streaming-text accumulation. Tests at the bottom add ~800 lines. AGENTS.md guidance: '~1000 lines is the split point.'\n\n## Proposed splits (per opus review)\n\n- app/state.rs — App struct + field initializers\n- app/input.rs — key handlers grouped by mode (Normal, Picker, ApprovalModal, Editing)\n- app/notification.rs — handle_notification + per-event variants (session.provider_status, session.assistant_text_finalized, mailbox.delivered, etc.)\n- render/header.rs, render/tabs.rs, render/command_center.rs, render/session_detail.rs, render/usage.rs, render/events.rs, render/modal.rs\n- mu_client.rs — already a separate file\n- tests move to app/tests/ or src/tests/\n\nTarget: <600 LOC per file.\n\n## Source\n\nopus-4-7 review event 194, 'What needs work' item 3. Operator awareness: mu-nk3 already did the analogous split for crates/mu-core/src/agent/loop_.rs.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-05-17T19:41:58.999121728Z","created_by":"tcovert","updated_at":"2026-05-19T18:12:11.050805891Z","source_repo":"mu","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["mu-tui","refactor","review-finding","split-large-file"],"comments":[{"id":43,"issue_id":"mu-lwiu","author":"tcovert","text":"LOC update 2026-05-19: file now 5253 lines on main (was 4530 when this bead was filed); iter-9 fix lands ~5815 after PR #108 merge.\n\nIter-9 fix did extract one pure helper (`shift_f8_indices_after_eviction`, ~12 LOC), which is the right shape for the eventual refactor — pure index arithmetic separated from the event loop, trivially testable. But the file keeps growing; nothing else got pulled out today.\n\nPer iter-10 reviewer (and prior iter-8 self-review), candidate extraction points worth tracking when this refactor happens:\n- F8 events explorer logic: `render_events_explorer` + its cursor/expand/scroll state machinery now spans ~250 lines inline; would slot cleanly into a `render/events_explorer.rs` module with the App fields it owns moved to a sub-struct.\n- F3 transcript scroll anchor + inline-emit logic (older, larger surface)\n- F5 usage dashboard\n- Each F-key view is a candidate self-contained module.\n\nPure-helpers worth extracting before the bigger split:\n- `compute_cursor_visibility_scroll(focused_visual_start, scroll_y, max_top, inner_height) -> Option<u16>` — would enable a unit test for the KEY_ISSUE-1-style \"fires-only-on-cursor-moved\" gating that iter-9 deferred. ~20 LOC + ~3 tests.\n- The `preview_truncate(s, char_count) -> String` char-boundary slicer (~5 LOC) — would let the UTF-8 panic edge case have a direct test instead of being implicit in the render fn.\n\nCross-refs:\n- PR #108 (mu-2ft part 1, merged 2026-05-19, merge sha edcfd53589e0): iter-7 worker + iter-9 orchestrator fix + iter-10 external review\n- Sibling bead mu-hgrj: same refactor pattern for mu-coding/src/serve/forwarder.rs (1261 LOC)\n","created_at":"2026-05-19T18:12:11Z"}]}
